<td>3</td>
<td>1</td>
<td>0</td>
<td>0</td>
<td>...</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>n = 4</td>
<td>1</td>
<td>4</td>
<td>6</td>
<td>4</td>
<td>1</td>
<td>0</td>
<td>...</td>
</tr>
</table>
<p>This extension preserves the property that the values in the <i>m</i>th column viewed as a function of <i>n</i> are fit by an order <i>m</i> polynomial, namely</p>
<dl>
<dd><img class="tex" alt="
{n \choose m} = \frac{1}{m!}\prod_{k=0}^{m-1} (n-k) = \frac{1}{m!}\prod_{k=1}^{m} (n-k+1)
" src="http://upload.wikimedia.org/math/8/2/2/822b872de68076740ab07df1fcef8067.png" />.</dd>
</dl>
<p>This extension also preserves the property that the values in the <i>n</i>th row correspond to the coefficients of <span class="texhtml">(1 + <i>x</i>)<sup><i>n</i></sup></span>:</p>
<dl>
<dd><img class="tex" alt="
(1+x)^n = \sum_{k=0}^\infty {n \choose k} x^n \quad |x| &lt; 1
" src="http://upload.wikimedia.org/math/0/8/9/08973d691367d0a7b1eecdc7fe474240.png" /></dd>
</dl>
<p>For example:</p>
<dl>
<dd><img class="tex" alt="
(1+x)^{-2} = 1-2x+3x^2-4x^3+... \quad |x| &lt; 1
" src="http://upload.wikimedia.org/math/9/7/0/9706d39eb6738185e160bb4bc7afbca1.png" /></dd>
</dl>
<p><br />
